Thermodynamics of the Triple-Process Cooking Method
To achieve the best possible taste, the master recipe rejects the "one-pot" simmering of raw meatballs in favor of a triple-process method: Searing, Braising, and Finishing.29
First, the meatballs must be subjected to high-heat searing—either pan-fried in olive oil or broiled in a  oven.3 This step initiates the Maillard reaction, creating a caramelized exterior crust that develops hundreds of new flavor compounds and ensures the meatball maintains its shape.3 Without this crust, the meatball remains "slimy" and lacks the textural contrast required for a sandwich.29
Second, the seared meatballs are moved into the simmering sauce for a "braising" phase. They should not simmer for hours; research indicates that exceeding  minutes in the sauce can cause the meatballs to become tough and dry as the muscle fibers tighten further.32 An optimal simmer of  to  minutes allows the meat to absorb the sauce's acidity while the core remains tender and juicy.29
Third, the final cook occurs during the sandwich assembly phase under a broiler. Here, the sauce, meat, and cheese are fused together at temperatures exceeding , creating a unified, molten filling.5
Structural Engineering: Bread Selection and the "Anti-Sog" Barrier
The bread is arguably the most critical component for a successful sandwich, yet it is the most frequent point of failure. A standard soft roll or hot dog bun will disintegrate under the weight and moisture of the meatballs and sauce.33 The master recipe requires a sturdy yet soft Italian roll or a high-quality baguette with a crackly crust and a resilient crumb.5
The "U-Gouge" vs. The "Hinge"
Architecture plays a significant role in the eating experience. While a standard hinge cut is common, the "U-gouge" or "canoe" technique—where a wedge of bread is removed from the top of the roll—creates a recessed channel that cradles the meatballs.38 This prevents the meatballs from sliding out of the sandwich during consumption and allows for a higher volume of sauce and cheese to be contained within the bread's boundaries.40
The Lipid Moisture Barrier and Cheese Shielding
To prevent sogginess, a moisture barrier must be established. This is achieved through two primary methods. First, the interior of the roll must be toasted with a layer of fat, specifically garlic butter (softened butter, minced garlic, parsley, and salt).12 The hydrophobic nature of the fat repels the water-based tomato sauce, keeping the bread crisp.27 Second, the "Cheese Barrier" involves placing a layer of sliced provolone or mozzarella on the bread before the meatballs and sauce are added.35 By melting this cheese onto the toasted bread first, the chef creates a waterproof seal that the sauce cannot penetrate, ensuring the sandwich remains structurally sound from the first bite to the last.42
